    <sect3 role="installation">
      <title>Installation of psutil</title>

      <para>
        Build the module:
      </para>

&build-wheel;

      <para>
        Now, as the &root; user:
      </para>

<screen role="root"><userinput>&install-wheel; psutil</userinput></screen>

<!--
      <para>
        This package does not have a working test suite.
      </para>
-->
      <para>
        In order to run the tests, the binary modules have to be copied:
      </para>

<screen remap='test'><userinput>cp build/lib*/psutil/*.so psutil</userinput></screen>

      <para>
        To test the results, issue:
      </para>

<screen remap='test'><userinput>python3 -m venv --system-site-packages testenv                      &amp;&amp;
testenv/bin/pip3 install colorama pytest-{instafail,subtests,xdist} \
                         psleak pyperf pypinfo                      &amp;&amp;
PSUTIL_DEBUG=1 testenv/bin/python3 -m pytest</userinput></screen>

      <itemizedlist spacing="compact">
        <listitem>
          <para>
            The tests named 
            <literal>TestSystemAPIs::test_disk_usage</literal>,
            <literal>TestFetchAllProcesses::test_all</literal>, and
            <literal>TestNetAPIs::test_net_if_addrs</literal>
            are known to fail.
          </para>
        </listitem>

        <listitem>
          <para>
	         The test named <literal>TestSystemNetIfAddrs::test_ips</literal>
	         is known to fail if IPv6 tunelling is enabled in the kernel.
          </para>
        </listitem>
        
        <listitem>
          <para>
           The test named
           <literal>TestAvailProcessAPIs::test_io_counters</literal> is known
           to fail if the kernel does not have
           <option>CONFIG_TASK_IO_ACCOUNTING</option> enabled.
          </para>
        </listitem>

        <!-- If Shadow is rebuilt with logind, it won't use utmp to track
             sessions no more and uses logind instead.  This test is invoking
             the "who" program which is from Coreutils (not Shadow) so it
             will print nothing and break the test.  Coreutils may be built
             with logind support but it's not enabled by default (even if
             libsystemd is installed), and we cannot simply enable it when
             we build it in LFS because at the time point libsystemd is not
             installed yet.  See the discussion about utmp Y2038 issue in
             the LFS Shadow page.  -->
        <listitem>
          <para>
            The test named <literal>TestExampleScripts::test_who</literal> is
            known to fail if the login manager does not write into
            <filename>/run/utmp</filename><phrase revision='systemd'> (note
            that due to the potential year 2038 problem, if
            <xref linkend='shadow'/> is already rebuilt in BLFS, it will stop
            writing into the file)</phrase>.
          </para>
        </listitem>

        <!-- The mechanism is a little different from above: here psutil
             itself parses utmp, so even if we build Coreutils with logind
             support it still won't help.  And it also doesn't like the
             utmp entry created by gdm (for gdm itself) for some
             reason.  -->
        <listitem>
          <para>
            The test named <literal>TestSystemAPIs::test_users</literal> is
            known to fail if the <filename>/run/utmp</filename> file contains
            an entry for the login screen.  It can also fail due to the same
            reason as <literal>TestExampleScripts::test_who</literal>.
          </para>
        </listitem>
      </itemizedlist>

    </sect3>

